{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18059"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18059"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.96,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74908"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60406"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5751"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25878"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74908"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA junior doctor accidentally administers twice the intended dose of paracetamol to a patient. The patient appears well and shows no signs of adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wait to see if symptoms develop before disclosing","Deny the error if questioned by the patient","Inform the patient about the error and monitor closely","Document the error but avoid telling the patient","Ask a senior colleague to take responsibility"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einform the patient about the error and monitor closely\u003C/strong\u003E. Open disclosure is an ethical and professional obligation that maintains trust in the therapeutic relationship. The patient has a right to know about events affecting their care, even if no harm has occurred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent poor ethical choices:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocument the error but avoid telling the patient\u003C/strong\u003E - This breaches the principle of transparency and patient autonomy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWait to see if symptoms develop before disclosing\u003C/strong\u003E - Delayed disclosure can damage trust and may prevent timely intervention\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsk a senior colleague to take responsibility\u003C/strong\u003E - This avoids personal accountability and professional responsibility\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeny the error if questioned by the patient\u003C/strong\u003E - Dishonesty violates ethical principles and can have legal consequences\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter disclosure, appropriate documentation, incident reporting, and clinical monitoring should follow. This approach supports a culture of openness and learning from errors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical errors should be disclosed to patients promptly and honestly to maintain trust and meet ethical obligations.","Open disclosure involves acknowledging the error, explaining what happened, expressing regret, and outlining steps to prevent recurrence.","Healthcare providers have both ethical and legal duties to inform patients about adverse events that affect their care."],"references":["Leung G, Porter G. Safety of candour: how protected are apologies in open disclosure? BMJ. 2019 Jun 13:365:l4047."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60406"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18059"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60406"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T09:38:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T09:39:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74908"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4947"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude7a","name":"Introduction to Clinical Sciences ","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":